{{short description|Flow of water in a river due to gravity }}
{{unreferenced|date=June 2014}}
[[Image:Stream in the redwoods.jpg|thumb|250px|right|The water in this stream forms varying currents as it makes its way downhill]]

A '''current''', in a [[river]] or [[stream]], is the flow of [[water]] influenced by [[gravity]] as the water moves [[wikt:downhill|downhill]] to reduce its [[potential energy]]. The current varies [[Three-dimensional space|spatially]] as well as [[Time|temporally]] within the stream, dependent upon the flow [[volume]] of water, [[stream gradient]], and [[Channel (geography)|channel]] geometry. In [[tidal zone]]s, the current in rivers and streams may reverse on the flood tide before resuming on the [[wikt:Ebb tide|ebb tide]].

