{{Infobox person | name = Ethel Pedley | image = Ethel Pedley.jpg | caption = Ethel Pedley's photograph from the author page of ''[[Dot and the Kangaroo]]''. | birth_name = Ethel Charlotte Pedley | birth_date = {{birth date|1859|06|19|df=yes}}<ref name=biography /> | birth_place = [[Acton, London]], England | death_date = {{death date and age|1898|08|06|1859|06|19|df=yes}} | death_place = [[Darlinghurst, New South Wales|Darlinghurst, Sydney, New South Wales]], Australia | death_cause = Cancer<ref name="biography">[http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/pedley-ethel-charlotte-8010 "Pedley, Ethel Charlotte (1859–1898)"], Norst, M., ''[[Australian Dictionary of Biography]] '' Volume 11, (MUP), 1988.</ref> | resting_place = [[Waverley Cemetery|Waverly Cemetery, Bronte, Sydney, New South Wales, Australia]] | occupation = Author, Musician | years_active = 1882-1898 | alma_mater = [[Royal Academy of Music]] (1882) }} {{Portal |Children's literature}}
[[File:Kangaroo cover-f.jpg|thumb|Cover of a 1920 publication of ''Dot and the Kangaroo'']] {{wikisource author}} '''Ethel Charlotte Pedley''' (19 June 1859 – 6 August 1898) was an [[Australia]]n [[author]] and musician. ==Early life== Ethel Charlotte Pedley was born on 19 June 1859 at Acton, near London.<ref name="ANDB">{{Citation|last=Norst|first=M.|title=Pedley, Ethel Charlotte (1859–1898)|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/pedley-ethel-charlotte-8010|work=Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher=National Centre of Biography, Australian National University|access-date=2018-06-19}}</ref> She was the daughter of Frederick Pedley and his wife Eliza, née Dolby.<ref name="ANDB" /> Pedley began piano lessons aged 5.<ref name="ANDB" /> Pedley migrated to Australia with her family in the 1870s but returned to London to study at the [[Royal Academy of Music]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article147279781 |title=Miss Ethel C. Pedley. |newspaper=[[Table Talk (magazine)|Table Talk]] |issue=218 |location=Victoria, Australia |date=23 August 1889 |accessdate=19 June 2018 |page=15 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> where she studied with her uncle Prosper Sainton, professor of violin, and won a medal.<ref name="ANDB" /> She was also trained by her aunt, the famous contralto [[Charlotte Sainton-Dolby]], at her Vocal Academy.<ref name="ANDB" />
==Career== ===Musician and music teacher=== Pedley returned to Sydney in 1882, and began teaching singing and the violin.<ref name="ANDB" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article237215097 |title=MISS PEDLEY'S "AT HOME." |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |issue=2764 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=28 May 1888 |accessdate=19 June 2018 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In 1896 Emmeline Woolley and Pedley visited London and persuaded the Associated Board of the [[Royal Academy of Music]] and the Royal College of Music to extend their examinations to the Australian colonies.<ref name="ANDB" /> Pedley was appointed the solo representative of the Royal Academy of Music for New South Wales.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://oa.anu.edu.au/obituary/pedley-ethel-charlotte-8010|title=Obituary - Ethel Charlotte Pedley - Obituaries Australia|website=oa.anu.edu.au|access-date=2018-06-19}}</ref> The first examiner visited in 1897.<ref name="ANDB" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article14139016 |title=DEATH OF MISS PEDLEY. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |issue=18,845 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=8 August 1898 |accessdate=19 June 2018 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>
===Author=== [[File:Dot and the Kangaroo, Author Page.jpg|right|thumb|A scan of a first edition copy of ''Dot and the Kangaroo'', which included a photograph of Pedley and a copy of her signature.]] Pedley's most well-known book is ''[[Dot and the Kangaroo]]'', which featured a little girl named Dot who becomes lost in the [[Australian outback]], and is helped to find her way back home by a friendly [[kangaroo]]. The illustrations were drawn by [[Frank P. Mahony]].<ref>{{Citation | author1=Pedley, Edith | author2=Mahony, Frank P. (Frank Prout), 1862-1917 | title=Dot and the kangaroo | publication-date=1899 | publisher=Tomas Burleigh | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/6580620 | accessdate=19 June 2018 }}</ref>
Pedley was a believer in the conservation of the Australian [[flora]] and [[fauna]], and usually wrote her books from this perspective, singling out 'man' as disconnected from nature and the rest of the animals.
Ethel's preface to ''Dot and the Kangaroo'' is as follows:
<poem style="font-style:italic"> ::To the children of Australia ::in the hope of enlisting their sympathies ::for the many beautiful, amiable, and frolicsome creatures ::of their fair land, ::whose extinction, through ruthless destruction, ::is being surely accomplished </poem>
