{{Refimprove|date=May 2015}} {{Infobox person | name = Joris van Spilbergen | image = Joris van Spilbergen 1568-1620.png | alt = <!-- descriptive text for use by the blind and visually impaired's speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software --> | caption = Joris van Spilbergen | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name --> | birth_date = 1568 | birth_place = [[Antwerp]] | death_date = 1629 (age 51–52) | death_place = [[Bergen op Zoom]] | nationality = [[Netherlands|Dutch]] | other_names = | occupation = Naval Officer | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = }} [[File:SpilbergenVimala.jpg|thumb|250px|Spilbergen meeting King [[Vimaladharmasuriya I of Kandy]] in 1602]] '''Joris van Spilbergen''' (1568 in [[Antwerp]] &ndash; 1620 in [[Bergen op Zoom]]) was a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] naval officer. Joris van Spilbergen was born in Antwerp in 1568.<ref name=is>[https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=nl&u=http://www.isgeschiedenis.nl/nieuws/joris-van-spilbergen-en-de-zeeslag-bij-arequipa/&prev=search Bakker, Michel. "Joris van Spilbergen and the Battle of Arequipa", ''IsGeschiedenis'', June 4, 2013]</ref>
His first major expedition was in 1596, when he sailed to Africa.
He then left for Asia on 5 May 1601, from Veere, a seaport on the island of Walcheren in Zealand, in command of the fleet of the company of [[Balthazar de Moucheron]] (a trading company before the establishment of the [[Dutch East India Company|VOC]]). His ships were the ''Ram'', ''Schaap'', and ''Lam''.<ref name=Anthonisz>[https://books.google.com/books?id=h2mkUharg6AC&pg=PA8&lpg=PA8&dq=joris+van+spilbergen&source=bl&ots=xcmsC0PXpg&sig=v-pb0ivbvWCfILmNykj2rrT9zpY&hl=en&sa=X&ei=bmBnVbyAGpKVyAST7IGgBA&sqi=2&ved=0CFIQ6AEwCw#v=onepage&q=joris%20van%20spilbergen&f=false Anthonisz, Richard Gerald. ''The Dutch in Ceylon'', Asian Educational Services, Colombo, 1929]</ref> Spilbergen met the king of Kandy ([[Sri Lanka]]) [[Vimala Dharma Suriya]] in 1602, and discussed the possibility of trade in [[cinnamon]].
In 1607, Spilbergen, onboard ''Aeolus'', was with [[Jacob van Heemskerk]] at the [[Battle of Gibraltar (1607)|Battle of Gibraltar]].
In 1614, he sailed beyond the [[Strait of Magellan]]<ref name=is/> with an expedition of five ships and raided the Spanish settlements on the coast of Mexico and South America. He fought the Spanish at [[Callao]], [[Acapulco]] and [[Navidad, Chile|Navided]].<ref name=Quanchi>Quanchi, ''Historical Dictionary of the Discovery and Exploration of the Pacific Islands'', page 233</ref> On October 26, he captured the pearl fishing ship ''San Francisco'' at Zacatula.<ref name=Myers>[https://books.google.com/books?id=-chO8R-i3PYC&pg=PA459&lpg=PA459&dq=joris+van+spilbergen&source=bl&ots=CJ3_XALEdL&sig=S746FRlB4G7O2FyachvHsl3vLUY&hl=en&sa=X&ei=KZZnVbu7EsGWyASi44P4Bw&ved=0CB0Q6AEwADgK#v=onepage&q=joris%20van%20spilbergen&f=false Myers, Paul A., ''North to California'', Llumina Press, 2004] {{ISBN|9781595262516}}</ref> He then sailed across the [[Pacific Ocean]] to the [[Mariana Islands]], the [[Philippine Islands]] and eventually to [[Ternate]] in the [[Maluku Islands]] in March 1616.<ref name= Quanchi/> He circumnavigated the earth, and returned to the Dutch Republic in 1617.
He died a poor man in [[Bergen op Zoom]] in 1620.
