{{Infobox Lunar mare
|name        = Lacus Gaudii
|image       = [[Image:Lacus-gaudii-clem1.jpg|300px|Lacus Gaudii]]
|caption     = 
|coordinates = {{coord|16.2|N|12.6|E|globe:moon_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}
|diameter    = 113 km
|eponym      = Lake of Delight
}}

'''Lacus Gaudii''' ([[Latin]] for "Lake of Delight") is a small [[lunar mare]] in the [[Terra Nivium]] region of the [[Moon]].<ref>Digital Lunar Orbiter Photographic Atlas of the Moon, Lunar and Planetary Institute [http://www.lpi.usra.edu/resources/lunar_orbiter/images/aimg/iv_097_h2.jpg Annotated Lunar Orbiter 4 Image 097 h2], based on Bowker and Hughes (NASA SP-206)</ref> It is located at 16.2° N, 12.6° E and is 113&nbsp;km in diameter.  The land lake borders with [[Lacus Hiemalis]] surrounding a small mountain formation in the middle, also in that location is a larger mountainous formation nearly surrounded by the small plain.  Further south is [[Lacus Lenitatis]] and narrowing bordering to the west is [[Lacus Doloris]].  In that eastern corridor lies next to [[Montes Haemus]] and just about 10&nbsp;km away is [[Mare Serenitatis]], the terrain in between are small mountains.  Southeast of the corridor is the crater [[Daubrée (crater)|Daubrée]] and the more prominent [[Menelaus (crater)|Menelaus]].

West of the lake is the prominent crater [[Manilius (crater)|Manilius]].  Inside the lake is Manilus' satellite crater lettered A in the eastern end and Z located in the middle.

